'''Greta Thunberg''' ({{IPA-sv|²greːta ²tʉːnˌbærj}}; born 3 January 2003) is a [[Swedes|Swedish]] climate activist. In August 2018, she became a prominent figure for starting the first [[school strike for climate]] outside the [[Riksdag|Swedish parliament building]], raising awareness of [[global warming]].<ref name=Guardian1>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2018/sep/01/swedish-15-year-old-cutting-class-to-fight-the-climate-crisis |title=The Swedish 15-year-old who's cutting class to fight the climate crisis |date=1 September 2018 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> In November 2018, she spoke at [[TED (conference)#TEDx|TEDxStockholm]], and in December 2018 she addressed the [[2018 United Nations Climate Change Conference|United Nations Climate Change Conference]].
== Life == Greta Thunberg was born on 3 January 2003.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lobbe |first1=Anne-Marie |title=À 15 ans, elle remet les dirigeants mondiaux à leur place! |url=http://www.sympatico.ca/actualites/decouvertes/a-15-ans-elle-remet-les-dirigeants-mondiaux-a-leur-place-1.8622552 |accessdate=3 January 2019 |publisher=Sympatico |date=13 December 2018 |language=fr}}</ref> Her mother is Swedish opera singer [[Malena Ernman]] and her father is actor Svante Thunberg,<ref name=Goodman>{{cite web|url=https://www.democracynow.org/2018/12/11/meet_the_15_year_old_swedish|title=School Strike for Climate: Meet 15-Year-Old Activist Greta Thunberg, Who Inspired a Global Movement|website=Democracy Now!}}</ref> who is named after his ancestor [[Svante Arrhenius]].<ref name=Goodman/><ref name=Guardian2>{{Cite news |author= Damian Carrington |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2018/dec/04/leaders-like-children-school-strike-founder-greta-thunberg-tells-un-climate-summit |title='Our leaders are like children', school strike founder tells climate summit |date=4 December 2018 |work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> Her grandfather is actor and director [[Olof Thunberg]].{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}
Thunberg has been diagnosed with [[autism]].<ref name=Newyorker1>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/our-columnists/the-fifteen-year-old-climate-activist-who-is-demanding-a-new-kind-of-politics |title=The Fifteen-Year-Old Climate Activist Who Is Demanding a New Kind of Politics |date=2 October 2018 |website=[[The New Yorker]]}}</ref> She insisted that her family become vegan and give up flying.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/world/europe/climate-crusading-schoolgirl-greta-thunberg-pleads-next-generations-case |title=Climate crusading schoolgirl Greta Thunberg pleads next generation's case |date=5 December 2018 |website=[[The Straits Times]] |language=en |access-date=22 December 2018}}</ref>
== Student strikes for climate == {{Main|School strike for climate}} [[File:Follow Greta! Strike for climate, placard, 2018 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Sign "Follow Greta! Strike for climate" in [[Berlin]] (14 December 2018).]]
On 20 August 2018, Thunberg, then in ninth grade, decided to not attend school until the [[Swedish general election, 2018|2018 Sweden general election]] on 9 September after [[2018 European heat wave|heat waves]] and [[2018 Sweden wildfires|wildfires]] in Sweden.<ref name=Guardian1/> Her demands were that the Swedish government reduce carbon emissions as per the [[Paris Agreement]], and she protested via sitting outside the [[Riksdag]] every day during school hours with the sign ''Skolstrejk för klimatet'' (school strike for the climate).<ref name=Newyorker1/>
After the general elections, she continued to strike only on Fridays, which gained worldwide attention. She inspired school students across the globe to take part in student strikes.<ref name=Guardian2/> As of December 2018, more than 20,000 students held strikes in at least 270 cities<ref name=Guardian2/> in countries including Australia, Austria,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/168763685@N07/albums|title=FridaysforFuture Vienna|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref> Belgium, Canada,<ref name=Larsen>{{Cite news |author=Karin Larsen |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/metro-vancouver-students-cut-class-to-demand-action-on-climate-change-1.4936647 |title=Metro Vancouver students cut class to demand action on climate change |date=7 December 2018 |work=CBC}}</ref> the Netherlands, Germany, Finland, Denmark, Japan, Switzerland,<ref name=ILJ>{{Cite news |url=https://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/global-warming_more-than-1-000-swiss-pupils-strike-over-climate/44636034 |title=More than 1,000 Swiss pupils strike over climate |date=21 December 2018 |work=swissinfo.ch}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.rts.ch/info/regions/autres-cantons/10091787-la-greve-du-climat-rassemble-des-centaines-d-etudiants-alemaniques.html |title=La "grève du climat" rassemble des centaines d'étudiants alémaniques |date=22 December 2018 |work=[[RTS Info]] |language=fr}}</ref> the United Kingdom and the United States.<ref name=Guardian2/><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.expressen.se/nyheter/klimat/klimatmanifestation-over-hela-landet-odesfraga/ |title=Klimatmanifestation över hela landet: "Ödesfråga" |date=30 November 2018 |work=[[Expressen]] |language=sv}}</ref> In Australia, thousands of school students were inspired by Thunberg to strike on Fridays, ignoring Prime Minister [[Scott Morrison]]'s comments of "more learning in schools and less activism".<ref name=Wilkinson>{{Cite news |author=Bard Wilkinson |url=https://edition-m.cnn.com/2018/11/30/australia/australia-school-climate-strike-scli-intl/index.html?r=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com%2Fsearch%3Fq%3Dclimate%2Bstrike%2BAustralia%26client%3Ducweb-b%26channel%3Dsb |title=Australian school children defy prime minister with climate strike |date=30 November 2018 |work=CNN}}</ref>
== Other activism == Greta Thunberg participated in the Rise for Climate demonstration outside the [[European Parliament]] in [[Brussels]] and the Declaration of Rebellion organized by [[Extinction Rebellion]] in [[London]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.commondreams.org/news/2018/10/31/our-darkest-hour-declaration-rebellion-new-group-vows-mass-civil-disobedience-save |title=This Is Our Darkest Hour: With Declaration of Rebellion, New Group Vows Mass Civil Disobedience to Save Planet |date=31 October 2018 |work=Common Dreams}}</ref>
On 24 November 2018, she spoke at [[TED (conference)#TEDx|TEDxStockholm]].<ref>{{cite web |title=TEDxStockholm Theme: Wonderland |url=https://www.ted.com/tedx/events/31825 |publisher=TED |accessdate=20 December 2018}}</ref> She speaks about autism as a way to explain why she cannot understand the inaction of governments and of citizens on climatic threat. Towards the conclusion of her talk, Thunberg said, "We've had thirty years of pep-talking and selling positive ideas. And I'm sorry, but it doesn't work. Because if it would have, the emissions would have gone down by now—they haven't."<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jon |first1=Queally |title=Depressed and Then Diagnosed With Autism, Greta Thunberg Explains Why Hope Cannot Save Planet But Bold Climate Action Still Can |url=https://www.commondreams.org/news/2018/12/19/depressed-and-then-diagnosed-autism-greta-thunberg-explains-why-hope-cannot-save |publisher=Common Dreams |accessdate=20 December 2018 |date=19 December 2018}}</ref>
On 4 December 2018, Thunberg addressed the [[COP24]] United Nations climate change summit.<ref>{{cite news |last1 = Carrington |first1 = Damian |title = 'Our leaders are like children', school strike founder tells climate summit |date = 4 December 2018 |work = The Guardian |location = London, United Kingdom |issn = 0261-3077 |url = https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2018/dec/04/leaders-like-children-school-strike-founder-greta-thunberg-tells-un-climate-summit |access-date = 4 December 2018}}</ref> On 12 December 2018, Thunberg again addressed the COP24 plenary assembly, stating:<ref>{{cite web |title=Greta Thunberg makes an impassioned appeal at UN climate change conference in Poland |url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/world/greta-thunberg-un-climate-change-conference-in-poland/video/ae124de8e21fc55c4027281c09d22fe4 |website=Herald Sun |publisher=NewsCorp Australia |accessdate=13 December 2018|date=13 December 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Thunberg |first1=Greta |title=You Are Stealing Our Future: Greta Thunberg, 15, Condemns the World's Inaction on Climate Change |url=https://www.democracynow.org/2018/12/13/you_are_stealing_our_future_greta |website=Democracy Now! |accessdate=13 December 2018}}</ref> {{quote | text ="You only speak of a green eternal economic growth because you are too scared of being unpopular. You only talk about moving forward with the same bad ideas that got us into this mess, even when the only sensible thing to do is pull the emergency brake. You are not mature enough to tell it like it is. Even that burden you leave to us children."
"And if solutions within the system are so impossible to find, then maybe we should change the system itself"|sign=|source=}}
On 23 January 2019, Thunberg arrived in [[Davos]] after her 32-hour train journey,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Larson |first1=Nina |title=Time to 'get angry', teen climate activist says in Davos |url=https://news.yahoo.com/time-angry-teen-climate-activist-says-davos-015904861.html |accessdate=24 January 2019 |work=news.yahoo.com |agency=AFP |date=24 January 2019 |quote="I think it is insane that people are gathered here to talk about the climate and they arrive here in private jet."}}</ref> in contrast to the many delegates who arrived by up to 1,500 individual private jets flights,<ref name="Indy2301">{{cite news |last1=Forrest |first1=Adam |title=Record number of private jets to fly into Davos conference addressing climate change |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/environment/davos-2019-private-jets-climate-change-world-economic-forum-summit-attenborough-a8742681.html |accessdate=24 January 2019 |work=The Independent |date=23 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref> to continue her climate campaign at the [[World Economic Forum]]. The following day she gave a speech in which she said:<ref name="CNN0125">{{cite news |last1=Kottasova |first1=Ivana |last2=Mackintosh |first2=Eliza |title=Teen activist blames Davos elite for climate crisis |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/01/25/europe/greta-thunberg-davos-world-economic-forum-intl/index.html |accessdate=26 January 2019 |work=CNN |date=25 January 2019}}</ref> {{quote | text = "Some people say that the climate crisis is something that we all have created, but that is not true, because if everyone is guilty then no one is to blame. And someone is to blame. Some people, some companies, some decision-makers in particular, have known exactly what priceless values they have been sacrificing to continue making unimaginable amounts of money. And I think many of you here today belong to that group of people."}}
== Prizes and awards == Greta Thunberg was one of the winners of [[Svenska Dagbladet]]'s debate article writing competition on the climate for young people in May 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.svd.se/vi-vet--och-vi-kan-gora-nagot-nu|title="Vi vet – och vi kan göra något nu" {{!}} SvD|website=SvD.se|language=sv|access-date=22 December 2018}}</ref> Thunberg was nominated for the electricity company Telge Energi's prize for children and young people who promote sustainable development, ''Children's Climate Prize,'' but declined because the finalists would have to fly to Stockholm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.etc.se/klimat/darfor-nobbar-greta-thunberg-klimatpriset|title=Därför nobbar Greta Thunberg klimatpriset|last=Gelin|first=Gustav|date=1 November 2018|website=ETC|language=sv|access-date=22 December 2018}}</ref> In November 2018, she was awarded the Fryshuset scholarship of the Young Role Model of the Year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aktuellhallbarhet.se/greta-thunberg-blir-arets-unga-forebild/|title=Greta Thunberg blir Årets unga förebild|date=22 November 2018|website=Aktuell Hållbarhet|language=sv-SE|access-date=22 December 2018}}</ref> In December 2018, ''Time'' magazine named Thunberg one of the world's 25 most influential teenagers of 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/5463721/most-influential-teens-2018/|title=TIME's 25 Most Influential Teens of 2018|website=Time|language=en|access-date=22 December 2018}}</ref>
